Here's the full migration. Your code has **three** Thread.Abort-related patterns:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| Cancellable work loop | `ProcessLoop` while loop | `CancellationToken` |
| ThreadAbortException + ResetAbort | catch block | `OperationCanceledException` |
| Thread.Abort() call | `Stop()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort equivalent needed; the loop condition handles exit
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key pitfalls to watch for

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept and respect the token.** If it blocks (e.g., `BlockingCollection.Take`, `Thread.Sleep`, socket read), it won't wake up on cancellation unless you pass the token:

```csharp
// Before — blocks indefinitely, can't be cancelled
var item = _queue.Take();

// After — throws OperationCanceledException when token fires
var item = _queue.Take(token);
```

If it uses `Thread.Sleep` or `WaitHandle.WaitOne`:
```csharp
// Before
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// After — wakes immediately on cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
```

**2. `Thread.Join` replaces `Thread.Sleep` + `IsAlive` check.** Your original `Stop()` slept 2 seconds then checked — `Join(timeout)` does this atomically and correctly.

**3. Cancellation is cooperative, not instant.** Unlike `Thread.Abort` which injected an exception at arbitrary points, `OperationCanceledException` only fires at checkpoints where the token is checked. Add checks inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running:

```csharp
private void ProcessItem(WorkItem item, CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var step in item.Steps)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Execute(step);
    }
}
```

**4. Always dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It allocates internal timers and callbacks. The `IDisposable` implementation on the class handles this.

**5. The `when` filter on the catch matters.** `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one from a nested operation.
